307. Range Sum Query - Mutable

Given an integer array nums, handle multiple queries of the following types:

Update the value of an element in nums.
Calculate the sum of the elements of nums between indices left and right inclusive where left <= right.
Implement the NumArray class:

NumArray(int[] nums) Initializes the object with the integer array nums.
void update(int index, int val) Updates the value of nums[index] to be val.
int sumRange(int left, int right) Returns the sum of the elements of nums between indices left and right inclusive (i.e. nums[left] + nums[left + 1] + ... + nums[right]).
 

Example 1:

Input
["NumArray", "sumRange", "update", "sumRange"]
[[[1, 3, 5]], [0, 2], [1, 2], [0, 2]]
Output
[null, 9, null, 8]

Explanation
NumArray numArray = new NumArray([1, 3, 5]);
numArray.sumRange(0, 2); // return 1 + 3 + 5 = 9
numArray.update(1, 2);   // nums = [1, 2, 5]
numArray.sumRange(0, 2); // return 1 + 2 + 5 = 8
 

Constraints:

1 <= nums.length <= 3 * 104
-100 <= nums[i] <= 100
0 <= index < nums.length
-100 <= val <= 100
0 <= left <= right < nums.length
At most 3 * 104 calls will be made to update and sumRange.

Intuition: 
      When you feel, sorting and prefix can't solve the problem alone.
      Because order also matters hence sorting is not applicable.
      And updates can happen in any index in any query, then prefix sums would invalidate as soon as we update in element at any index.
      Hence brute force to scan every range/segment in each query would be huge ( as O(N) everytime ).
      So it pushes us to think what iff we would have sum of different contingous range's sums stored.
      And in each query , if we would have the discipline to go in a define direction to calculate through only required blocks of segments, then it might give us reduced algo.
      That's what we can get in segment trees.
      In segment tree, to follow discpiline, we divide the array into segments of contigous blocks and storing their sum in different array.
      That way we would have 2 * N - 1 elements. yeah, little more we have to let it go on space.
      And we can reach till valid depth/chain of segments in O( log N ).


class NumArray {
    vector<int>segTree;
    int N;
public:
    // building segment Tree. first 2 index handling the segments of the array and the nodeIdx taking care of the segTree index where the new element needs to go.
    void buildSegTree(vector<int> & nums, int start, int end, int nodeIdx) {
        if(start == end) {
            segTree[nodeIdx] = nums[start];
            return;
        }
        int mid = (start + end) >> 1;
        buildSegTree(nums, start, mid, nodeIdx * 2 + 1);
        buildSegTree(nums, mid+1, end, nodeIdx * 2 + 2);
        segTree[nodeIdx] = segTree[nodeIdx * 2 + 1] + segTree[nodeIdx * 2 + 2];
    }

    NumArray(vector<int>& nums) {
        N = nums.size();
        segTree.resize(N * 4);
        buildSegTree(nums, 0, N - 1, 0); // first 2 args (start and end index in nums), 3rd arg is where we starting to put the first or root of segTree
    }
    
    void updateSegTree(const int & index, const int & val, int start, int end, int nodeIdx) {
        if(start == end) {
            segTree[nodeIdx] = val;
            return;
        }
        int mid = (start + end) >> 1;
        if(mid >= index) updateSegTree(index, val, start, mid, nodeIdx * 2 + 1);
        else updateSegTree(index, val, mid+1, end, nodeIdx * 2 + 2);
        segTree[nodeIdx] = segTree[nodeIdx * 2 + 1] + segTree[nodeIdx * 2 + 2];
    }

    void update(int index, int val) {
        updateSegTree(index, val, 0, N-1, 0);
    }
    
    int getSegTreeSumRange(const int & ql, const int & qr, int start, int end, int nodeIdx) {
        if(ql > end || qr < start) return 0;
        if(ql <= start && qr >= end) return segTree[nodeIdx];
        int mid = (start + end) >> 1;
        return getSegTreeSumRange(ql, qr, start, mid, nodeIdx * 2 + 1) + 
                getSegTreeSumRange(ql, qr, mid+1, end, nodeIdx * 2 + 2);
    }

    int sumRange(int left, int right) {
        return getSegTreeSumRange(left, right, 0, N-1, 0);
    }
};

/**
 * Your NumArray object will be instantiated and called as such:
 * NumArray* obj = new NumArray(nums);
 * obj->update(index,val);
 * int param_2 = obj->sumRange(left,right);
 */


// T.C. : O(N) one time for building segment tree, and then O( log N ) for each query
// S.C. : O(N) or O(4N)
